Why do you want it though?

There are two advantages over traditional sites.

1. No ads (which means no annoying ads, no moral quandry of whether to block them or not, and no demonitization of political views)
2. You do not have to buy into a corporate infrastructure and it's financial backers in order to get content, and it is more likely that there will be a single standard worked on by multiple coops or corporations. Think everyone using .mp3 or .jpg vs using proprietary formats like .docx or .wav.

Youtube is a one stop shop only because it is a monopoly. Decentralizing the system and standardizing it allows you to avoid monopoly while still having only one "system" with global search powers.

Google and Bing acheive this btw by just being neutral and not serving the content they show you themselves, and wikipedia achieves this by being both popular and nonprofit.
